\f0\fs24 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Cosmicflows-4, the fourth release in Brent Tully's long-running compilation, ~56,000 galaxies with the Tully\'96Fisher subset providing the dominant H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  leverage at 75.1 \'b1 0.2 stat \'b1 3 sys) and the historical arc through CF1\'96CF3. Now that we've worked through Tully\'96Fisher, the Fundamental Plane, Pop-II, and the broader H0DN landscape, let me give you the deeper picture: what makes CF4 conceptually distinctive, why it sits where it does in the network.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 What CF4 actually is \'97 beyond the catalog description\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 The trap when discussing CF4 is treating it like just another distance compilation. It's not. CF4 is a 
\f2\b velocity-field reconstruction enterprise
\f0\b0  that happens to produce H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  as a byproduct.\
The conceptual structure goes like this:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Galaxies have measured 
\f2\b redshifts
\f0\b0  $cz_\{\\rm obs\}$, which decompose into 
\f2\b Hubble flow
\f0\b0  ($H_0 d$) plus 
\f2\b peculiar velocity
\f0\b0  ($v_p$). If you measure $d$ independently (via TF, FP, SBF, TRGB, etc.) and you know $cz_\{\\rm obs\}$, you get $v_p$ \'97 and the 
\f3\i map
\f0\i0  of $v_p$ across many galaxies reconstructs the gravitationally-induced velocity field of the local universe.\
Cosmicflows is fundamentally about that map. The Laniakea Supercluster (Tully+14), the Dipole Repeller (Hoffman+17), the Shapley Concentration's gravitational influence on local kinematics \'97 all these are CF-program science products. The H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurement is not the headline result of CF4 in Tully's framing; it's a calibration step required to do the mapping correctly.\
This matters for how to interpret CF4-derived H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  values:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 1. The H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  value depends on getting the velocity field right.
\f0\b0  If your peculiar-velocity model is biased, your H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  is biased. CF4's reconstruction iterates between distance estimates and PV models, with significant feedback between the two.\

\f2\b 2. CF4 internally constrains H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  very tightly statistically.
\f0\b0  With ~10,000 galaxies in the TF subset, the formal statistical error on H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  is \'b10.2 \'97 but this assumes the PV model is correctly subtracted. The realistic \'b13 systematic is dominated by uncertainty in the PV model and in the TF zero point, not by any per-galaxy distance scatter.\

\f2\b 3. The CF4 H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  is a Hubble-flow zero-point measurement, not a single-rung calibration.
\f0\b0  When the catalog reports "H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 75.1," what it means physically is "the asymptotic value of $cz/d$ in the limit of large $d$, where peculiar velocities average out." This is conceptually different from SH0ES's "H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  from the SN Ia Hubble diagram zero point" \'97 both are valid definitions of H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 , but the CF4 version directly couples H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  to the assumed PV field structure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 The CF4 distance compilation at the rung level\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

