\cf0 The catalog homogenizes all of these to a common zero-point \'97 a non-trivial calibration step that involves cross-comparing distances to galaxies measured by multiple methods and adjusting individual methods' zero points to bring them into agreement.\
The combined CF4 H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  from Tully+23 (using all methods, weighted by per-galaxy precision) is 
\f2\b 74.6 \'b1 0.8 (stat) \'b1 3.0 (sys)
\f0\b0 . The per-method values feed into this with weights determined by sample size, scatter, and assumed independence.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 Why the CF4 H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  is hard to interpret cleanly\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Three issues that make the headline CF4 H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  value harder to use than it looks:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 1. The CF4 zero-point is internal, not external.
\f0\b0  The catalog's TF zero point is calibrated by tying TF-distance galaxies to the small subset that also have Cepheid or TRGB distances. Different choices about which calibrators to anchor to (Cepheid-only vs Cepheid+TRGB vs full subset) shift the CF4 H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  by ~1 km/s/Mpc. Boubel+24 reanalyzed the same TF data with Cepheid-only anchoring and got H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 73.3 \'b1 2.1 (stat) \'b1 3.5 (sys), versus K20's 75.1 \'b1 0.2 (stat) \'b1 3 (sys). Same data, different anchoring choice, ~1.8 km/s/Mpc difference.\

\f2\b 2. Dependence on the PV model.
\f0\b0  The local PV field has structure on scales ranging from individual cluster infall (Virgo) to the Shapley Concentration's tidal influence (~30 Mpc/h). CF4 assumes a particular PV model in solving for distances; using a different PV model (e.g., 2M++, the SDSS reconstruction, or the no-correction Pesce-style approach) shifts H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  by ~2 km/s/Mpc. This is a real systematic, not a small effect.\

\f2\b 3. The "stat vs sys" decomposition is generous to the systematic.
\f0\b0  \'b10.2 statistical with \'b13 systematic is the kind of error budget where the central value is essentially defined by the systematic \'97 the \'b10.2 is illusory in any practical sense. For purposes of comparing to other H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurements, treat CF4 as 
\f2\b 75 \'b1 3
\f0\b0  and ignore the inner statistical error bar.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 CF4 in the H0DN figure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 CF4 is the right-hand portion of the network \'97 the 
\f2\b Hubble-flow extension
\f0\b0  that goes far beyond where SN Ia samples reach efficiently. SN Ia in calibrated rung-2 hosts get you out to maybe ~10,000 km/s. TF/FP/SBF in CF4 reach 15,000+ km/s for TF and ~30,000 km/s for FP. This extends the Hubble-flow lever arm dramatically.\
But the H0DN figure is careful to note that 
\f2\b CF4 results don't dominate the H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  inference
\f0\b0 , despite their large sample sizes. The reason: they have larger systematic errors per galaxy than SN Ia methods, so even with vastly more galaxies they don't beat SN Ia statistically. A method that goes from "10
\f1 \uc0\u8308 
\f0  TF measurements at 20% per-galaxy scatter" to "10\'b3 SN Ia at 7% per-galaxy scatter" gives the 
\f3\i same
\f0\i0  statistical precision, and the SN Ia have much smaller systematics.\
What CF4 
\f3\i does
\f0\i0  contribute to the H0DN inference:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 1. PV-field characterization.
\f0\b0  CF4's PV map is used to correct other methods (especially MCP, where six galaxies are not enough to internally average over PVs). In this role, CF4 is a calibration input rather than an H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  measurement per se.\

\f2\b 2. A different lever arm.
\f0\b0  CF4 reaches Hubble flow at higher z than SN Ia samples, and uses TF spirals + FP ellipticals \'97 completely different host samples than SN Ia. If CF4 H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  were systematically 
\f3\i low
\f0\i0  relative to SN Ia, this would be a smoking gun for SN Ia\'96specific systematics. It isn't (CF4 is high, ~75); the consistency adds another point of robustness.\

\f2\b 3. Additional robustness checks.
\f0\b0  CF4's combination with SBF and TRGB at the calibration step gives an internally homogenized distance compilation that the H0DN paper uses in some of its variant analyses.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 CF4 vs the rest of the local H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  measurements\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

