\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 CF4 sits at high H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  alongside MCP, adh0cc, and DESI FP \'97 the methods that are 
\f2\b not
\f0\b0  primarily SN Ia\'96anchored. This pattern is meaningful: methods that don't share the SN Ia rung consistently land at ~74\'9676, while methods that do share the SN Ia rung land at ~73 (SH0ES) or ~70 (CCHP).\
The interpretive question this raises: is the SN Ia rung pulling the SH0ES result 
\f3\i down
\f0\i0  slightly relative to the other methods, or is the non-SN Ia rung systematically slightly high due to PV systematics or zero-point drift? The H0DN paper handles this in its covariance machinery; for your purposes, the takeaway is that the methods cluster within ~3 km/s/Mpc of each other, and 
\f3\i all
\f0\i0  are inconsistent with Planck.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 The CF4 / Cosmicflows series in the bigger picture\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 A useful conceptual frame: 
\f2\b the Cosmicflows program is the closest thing in the H
\f4 \uc0\u8320 
\f2  debate to what CMB experiments are at the early-time end
\f0\b0  \'97 large-volume statistical sampling of the universe's velocity structure, with H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  as one extracted parameter from a much broader analysis. Just as Planck doesn't really measure H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  directly but rather extracts it from a global fit to the CMB power spectrum, CF4 doesn't really measure H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  directly but extracts it from the global fit to the local velocity field.\
This means CF4's failure modes are more like Planck's failure modes (parametric model assumptions, residual modeling errors at large scales) than like SH0ES's failure modes (per-rung systematic at one specific calibration step). Different epistemological flavor, even though both nominally measure H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0 .\
For the H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  tension specifically, this is a useful framing: if you trust both Planck's and CF4's parametric reconstructions equally, you'd note that they disagree (67 vs 75). The disagreement is roughly the same magnitude as the tension. This is a "global model" vs "global model" comparison that's complementary to the SH0ES vs Planck "rung-by-rung" comparison.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 Recent and upcoming developments\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 CF4's near-term evolution:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 1. WALLABY
\f0\b0  \'97 the ASKAP Wide-field ASKAP L-band Legacy All-sky Blind surveY. WALLABY is producing H I distance measurements for ~10
\f1 \uc0\u8309 
\f0  spirals over the southern sky, ~10\'d7 the CF4 TF sample. First results (Courtois+24, Said+24) suggest TF zero points consistent with CF4 within errors but tighten the systematic floor. The WALLABY-era TF H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  should reach ~75 \'b1 1.5\'962 once final calibration is settled.\

\f2\b 2. DESI Peculiar Velocity Survey
\f0\b0  \'97 DESI's spectroscopy is providing FP measurements for ~10
\f1 \uc0\u8310 
\f0  early-type galaxies, the largest FP sample ever. Said+25 reports H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  = 76.05 \'b1 0.35 (stat) \'b1 1.5 (sys) \'97 comparable in precision to SH0ES. This is a big deal: the FP H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  has gone from being a noisy cross-check to a comparably precise standalone measurement.\

\f2\b 3. 4HS (4MOST Hemisphere Survey)
\f0\b0  \'97 the southern-hemisphere counterpart to DESI for FP work, coming online ~2025\'962027.\
The CF4 era is transitioning to a "PV survey era" where TF and FP samples are entering Planck-like sample sizes. The H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  leverage is going to come increasingly from this direction rather than from ladder-based methods, and the question of whether CF/PV-anchored H
\f1 \uc0\u8320 
\f0  values converge on SH0ES (73) or on something higher (75\'9676) will be increasingly answerable.\
}